new='PASSAGES["Level 15"]=[{title:"Mental Health in Young People",text:"The mental health crisis among adolescents in the developed world predates the COVID-19 pandemic but was dramatically accelerated by it. Rates of anxiety, depression, and self-harm among young people aged 12 to 17 began rising measurably around 2012, a date that coincides with the widespread adoption of smartphones and social media platforms. Researchers including psychologist Jean Twenge have argued that the correlation is causal, pointing to the displacement of in-person socializing by screen-based interaction and the well-documented psychological effects of social comparison on developing identities. Others caution that correlation does not establish causation and note that rising academic pressure, economic instability, and awareness of global crises may be equally significant contributors. The pandemic closed schools, isolated adolescents from peer relationships that are developmentally critical, and created widespread uncertainty about the future. Studies conducted during 2020 and 2021 documented sharp increases in depression and anxiety symptoms globally. The long-term effects are still being measured. What is clear is that the mental health infrastructure in most countries was inadequate before the crisis and has not kept pace with growing demand. Reducing stigma, increasing access to care, and redesigning school environments to prioritize wellbeing alongside academic achievement are among the approaches researchers and advocates are calling for.",qs:["What two possible explanations does the passage offer for rising mental health challenges?","Why does the author note that correlation does not establish causation?","What does the passage identify as the most significant gap in the current response?","What changes to your school environment do you think would most support student wellbeing?"]},{title:"How Climate Change Affects Sports",text:"Climate change is restructuring the economics, logistics, and culture of sport in ways that are only beginning to be fully understood. At the recreational level the effects are already visible. Ski resorts in the Alps, Rockies, and Appalachians have seen their viable operating seasons contract by weeks or months over the past three decades as snowfall becomes less reliable and temperatures rise. Many smaller resorts have closed permanently. At the elite level the complications are different but equally significant. Marathon organizers have shifted race start times to pre-dawn hours to avoid dangerous heat. The International Olympic Committee has moved outdoor summer events to cooler early morning slots and is actively evaluating whether certain host city climates remain viable. Coral bleaching driven by ocean warming has degraded surf breaks that have defined competitive surfing for generations. Wildfire smoke has forced the cancellation of outdoor sporting events across the western United States with increasing frequency. Sports organizations are responding along two tracks simultaneously: adaptation, modifying how and where sport is practised to accommodate changed conditions, and mitigation, reducing their own carbon footprints through renewable energy, sustainable venue design, and carbon offset programmes.",qs:["What two tracks are sports organizations using to respond to climate change?","How has climate change affected both recreational and elite sport differently?","What does the decline of ski resorts suggest about the economic risks of climate change?","Which sport do you think faces the greatest threat from climate change and why?"]},{title:"The History of Hip-Hop",text:"Hip-hop emerged in the South Bronx in the summer of 1973, born from conditions of economic devastation, municipal neglect, and cultural creativity. The borough had been effectively abandoned by city planners, its infrastructure crumbling, its youth unemployment rate among the highest in the country. In that context DJ Kool Herc, a Jamaican immigrant, developed a technique at a back-to-school party in the recreation room of 1520 Sedgwick Avenue that would change music permanently. He used two turntables to isolate and extend the percussive break sections of funk and soul records — the moments when the drums dropped and the crowd went wildest — creating an unbroken loop of rhythm that dancers could move to indefinitely. From that technical innovation four interconnected art forms crystallized: DJing, MCing, breakdancing, and graffiti writing. Each was a form of expression that required no expensive equipment or institutional permission. Over the following decades hip-hop spread from the Bronx to every borough, every city, and eventually every country on earth, carrying with it the voices of communities that mainstream media had systematically excluded. Today it is the most streamed genre of music globally, a 25 billion dollar industry, and a primary lens through which youth culture understands itself.",qs:["What social conditions gave rise to hip-hop?","How did DJ Kool Herc\'s technique work and why was it significant?","What does the passage mean when it says hip-hop required no institutional permission?","How does knowing the origins of hip-hop change how you understand the music?"]}];\n'
